texts: Seated in the back of a car, Graham Kingly shifted his gaze from outside to the information displayed on the car's windshield.
It showed that the destination—Uminomori—was half an hour away.
The car was currently parked at the side of the road in Nihonbashi, however.
He was soon joined by Ewan Okuda, who'd brought a large object with him.
All business has been taken care of. Drive.
The two were sitting directly beside one other, but they didn't so much as exchange a glance.
Between them was the huge stuffed animal that Ewan had brought.
...How many of these have you bought now?
It's a small price to pay to keep Asuma manageable. It makes your job easier too, doesn't it?
So these are just to keep him in a good mood? Is that really all there is to it?
More importantly, I was never told that GAIA needed maintenance.
Yes. You weren't. Because there's no such maintenance.
So you lied just to get through that mess?
It's far better than having Asuma take part in such useless meetings.
Graham could not deny that sentiment.
Hardly any of this makes sense.
You're a soldier. Aren't you used to being kept in the dark?
I've been a soldier for years, but I've never been in a situation like this.
The brat that showed up outta nowhere was especially weird...
He knew exactly when we'd be told to retreat. Down to the second.
There's no way he could have known that without hacking a military sat.
Wizard-tier hackers who could access military satellites without leaving a trace were few and far between.
And such activity would make you an enemy of the USA. Graham didn't believe this operation warranted such feats.
That's why he doubted that hacking was at the center of it all.
Someone leak our info to that twerp?
Or does he just have a good intuition?
Asuma had something to say about what happened too.
He said that "things are going differently from the simulation."
In a way he couldn't grasp, those words put Graham ill at ease.
